1. Introduction¶

1.1 Write a neural network model that runs on the image data and outputs confusion matrix and accuracy. Let us not bother with good accuracy here, just get it to run. Feel free to adapt the the squares-circles, or cats-dogs example code (note: the latter uses multicolor images!).

This problem set uses a neural network structure adopted from cats-n-dogs.py. The introductory model uses images from all four languages. Images are forced to a shape of 200x500 with one color channel.

This model runs very quickly as two epochs do not train the model very thoroughly. To simplify discussion surrounding the exact layers of the neural network, we will discuss complexity in terms of the number of parameters used in the model. Here, 78,468 parameters are included.

The model has 0.4431 accuracy. Clearly speed is favored over accuracy as two epochs with few parameters allow it to run in less than a minute. We can see that the model is prone to classifying EN images as ZN images, which is confusing since the characters in their respective languages look very different.

# sequential (not recursive) model (one input, one output)
model=Sequential()

model.add(Conv2D(16,
                 kernel_size=3,
                 strides=2,
                 activation='relu',
                 input_shape=(targetWidth, targetHeight, channels)))
model.add(BatchNormalization())
model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=3))
model.add(Dropout(0.25))

model.add(Conv2D(8,
                 kernel_size=3,
                 activation='relu'))
model.add(BatchNormalization())
model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))
model.add(Dropout(0.25))

model.add(Flatten())
model.add(Dense(16, activation='relu'))
model.add(BatchNormalization())
model.add(Dropout(0.5))
model.add(Dense(8, activation='softmax'))

model.add(Dense(nCategories, activation='softmax'))

model.compile(loss='categorical_crossentropy',
              metrics=['accuracy'])
model.summary()

2. EN vs. ZN¶

Attempt 1: 78k Parameters, 1 Epoch¶

This is the first attempt to distinguish EN from ZN. A for loop is implemented to extract the language classification of each file and subsequently filter out DA and RU. This model is similar to the last one in that the neural network uses a similar structure with 78,336 parameters. However, one epoch is used so we can quickly test the model.

As a test, the dimensions in the second to last dense layer was reduced to 2. This slightly reduced the number of parameters. The model produced 0.9988 accuracy despite this change as it distinguished EN from ZN. With only four mislabeled images, this is extremely good.

The ending chunks of this model plot the four images mislabeled by the model. One image contains no characters, and the other is ZN but it contains mostly EN characters. If the data was cleaned before use to exclude these two outliers, the model would have 0.9994 accuracy under similar conditions.

predicted EN ZN
EN 2038 0
ZN 4 1345

Accuracy 0.9988

## Print and plot misclassified results
wrongResults = testResults[testResults.predicted != testResults.category]
rows = np.random.choice(wrongResults.index, min(4, wrongResults.shape[0]), replace=False)
print("Example wrong results")
print(wrongResults.sample(min(10, wrongResults.shape[0])))
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 12))
index = 1
for row in rows:
    filename = wrongResults.loc[row, 'filename']
    predicted = wrongResults.loc[row, 'predicted']
    img = load_img(os.path.join(imgDir, "test", filename), target_size=imageSize)
    plt.subplot(2, 2, index)
    plt.imshow(img)
    plt.xlabel(filename + " ({})".format(predicted))
    index += 1
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Attempt 2: 20M parameters, 5 Epochs¶

This model is an attempt to perfectly distinguish EN/ZN at the cost of a long runtime. This model uses 20 million parameters, runs for 5 epochs, and takes just over 25 minutes to run.

Two more testing images were correctly classified in this model compared to the last one. It has over 255 times more parameters than the previous model, so we can see this improvement in accuracy is not very proportional. 20 million parameters in unnecessary - we can likely achieve a more realistic runtime while managing a reasonable accuracy (above 0.98).

# sequential (not recursive) model (one input, one output)
model=Sequential()

model.add(Conv2D(16,
                 kernel_size=3,
                 strides=2,
                 activation='relu',
                 input_shape=(targetWidth, targetHeight, channels)))
model.add(BatchNormalization())
model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=3))
model.add(Dropout(0.25))

model.add(Conv2D(8,
                 kernel_size=3,
                 activation='relu'))
model.add(BatchNormalization())
model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))
model.add(Dropout(0.25))

model.add(Flatten())
model.add(Dense(16, activation='relu'))
model.add(BatchNormalization())
model.add(Dropout(0.5))
model.add(Dense(2, activation='softmax'))

model.add(Dense(nCategories, activation='softmax'))

              metrics=['accuracy'])

from PIL import Image
import os.path, sys

def crop(read_path, write_path, dirs):
  for item in dirs:
    fullpath = os.path.join(read_path,item)
    if os.path.isfile(fullpath):
      im = Image.open(fullpath)
      f, e = os.path.splitext(fullpath)
      imCrop = im.crop((0, 0, 100, 100))
      imCrop.save(write_path + item)

# crop train data
read_path = "../../data/language/train"
write_path = "../../data/language/crop_train/"
dirs = os.listdir(read_path)
crop(read_path, write_path, dirs)

# crop test data
read_path = "../../data/language/test"
write_path = "../../data/language/crop_test/"
dirs = os.listdir(read_path)
crop(read_path, write_path, dirs)

4. Other Languages¶

EN, ZN, RU¶

This model adds in RU to the existing EN and ZN model. An issue that occurred during testing is that the second to last dense layer used 2 dimensions. This means that when the model had built a knowledge of three languages, it was forced to combine two languages into one channel. This was addressed by restoring the dense layer to have 8 dimensions (at least more than 3) and the model saw an improvement.

The confusion matrix performs extremely well with 78,459 parameters and 2 epochs. The most common issue with this model is that some RU images were classified as EN by the model.

# sequential (not recursive) model (one input, one output)
model=Sequential()

model.add(Conv2D(16,
                 kernel_size=3,
                 strides=2,
                 activation='relu',
                 input_shape=(targetWidth, targetHeight, channels)))
model.add(BatchNormalization())
model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=3))
model.add(Dropout(0.25))

model.add(Conv2D(8,
                 kernel_size=3,
                 activation='relu'))
model.add(BatchNormalization())
model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))
model.add(Dropout(0.25))

model.add(Flatten())
model.add(Dense(16, activation='relu'))
model.add(BatchNormalization())
model.add(Dropout(0.5))
model.add(Dense(8, activation='softmax'))

model.add(Dense(nCategories, activation='softmax'))

model.compile(loss='categorical_crossentropy',
              metrics=['accuracy'])
model.summary()

EN, ZN, RU, DA¶

The final model includes all languages: EN, ZN, RU, and DA. It uses 78,468 parameters. DA and EN characters look very similar - this is likely to be an issue with image classification.

From the confusion matrix, we can immediately tell that this model did excellent work identifying ZN images. As expected, the most common issue this model had was distinguishing DA and EN. It predicted about 7 times DA images as EN than it did EN images as DA.
